@wordwrap
@tab 8

@node sect0 "Name"
samdir - display a SAMDOS directory 
@endnode

@node sect1 "Synopsis"
@{b}samdir@{ub} [ @{b}-diskfile @{ub}@{i}file@{ui} ] [ @{b}!@{ub} | @{b}-short@{ub} ] [ @{b}?@{ub} | @{b}-all@{ub} ] [ samdosfile... ] 
@endnode

@node sect2 "Description"
@{i}Samdir@{ui} displays the contents of a SAMDOS directory. The directory may be taken from a disk file instead of a real floppy by setting the environment variable SAMDISKFILE to the name of the image file or by supplying the @{b}-diskfile @{ub}@{i}file@{ui} flag.  If used this flag must be written first on the command line. It may be abbreviated to @{b}-disk @{ub}@{i}file.@{ui} 

@{i}Samdir@{ui} will allow the following command line options: 



· @{b}!@{ub} or @{b}-short@{ub} @{lindent 3}
Short output.  This option will print the filenames sorted in ASCII order across the page, three to a line, without displaying the file size or type. @{lindent 0}

· @{b}?@{ub} or @{b}-all@{ub} @{lindent 3}
This option displays all files on the disk matching the given names. Normally only those files in the current directory are considered. This option also causes leading directory names specified with the given file names to be ignored. @{lindent 0}

If no filename is given then @{i}samdir@{ui} displays the directory of the whole disk.  Otherwise it displays the named files, which may contain wildcard characters.  The use of wildcards or spaces will require the names to be enclosed in quotes to protect them from the shell. 

If the disk is a MasterDOS disk then the given filenames may be full path names; otherwise @{i}samdir@{ui} will only look in the current directory (see @{i}samtools@{ui}(1) for further information).  Directories are ignored for SAMDOS disks. If a supplied filename names a directory on a MasterDOS disk then the directory itself will be listed.  In order to list the contents of the directory, add a trailing slash. 


@endnode

@node sect3 "See Also"
samtools(1) 
@endnode
